,of Renton ser\nI vices will be made later\n\u2014H. Garrison. State secretary of\nthe Y. M. C. A., was in tlie city yes\nterday conferring with Fred Fox\nchairman of the State organization.\nPlans were perfected to strengthen\nthe work throughout the State and a\ncommittee o fprominent Y. M. C. A.\nofficials and business men will meet\nshortly to discuss the plans and or\nganize.\n\u2014Reverend A. I). Rowan, pastor o>\nthe Jerusalem Itaptist Church, col\nored, is holding a most successful re\ni vival there. The church is being\nJ crowded nightly and there have been\nmore than sixty additions to the\nj church since it began, \u201d1 have stir\nI red tip the population in the whole\nsouth end of the town,\u2019 said Rev.\nI Rowan yesterday.\n\u2014Tlie Ragles will give a St. Pat\ni rick's ball at their hall on West Sec\nond avenue on the night of March IT.\nGreen will be the prevailing color.\nJjjoe Dillon\u2019s orchestra will furnish the\n1 music. The .committee in charge of\nThe Arkansas river is covered\nwith an oily fluid which is attraet\nw Little Rock, recently and c'ausod no\nlittle comment. The <>;b waters\n|j i have finally reached this city. Ui'cr\n1 men are unable to explain the ap\npearance of the oil on he w*t*i\n\u2014W. H. Westbrook, the well\nknown local commission man. re\ncently returned from a business trip\nin Cleveland county. He reports the\nbuilding of a new telephone lino\nfrom Pansy to Risou and it is stated\n3 that it is the intentionu of the\ngj builders to bring tlio line into Pine\nh iMuff. The now line will connect the\nI homes of many farmers in Clevo\njj land, Grant and. Jefferson counties.\nIt is rumored that a company, com\nI posed of planters, is building the\nnew lini\nFRISCO INDICTED\nSt. Louis, March 2.\u2014Indictments\nwere returned today by the federal\ngrand jury against the St. Louts\nSan Francisco railroad for grant'ng\nrebates, and Chapman Dewey\nLumber Company for accepting re\nbates. Thero are thirteen counts\nbased on shipments from the state\nof Arkansas during 1905.\naHlfcF MENTION.\n\n\nreturned\nMiss Lillian Hudson ha\nfrom a visit to friends at Altheimer.\ni\u2019lerk Kd Duval, of Grant county,\nwas a business visitor in the city yes\nI\u2019rici\nterday.\nI\u2019aul Hut rk\nwhere he will visit\noral days.\nDoctor Charles\nlas. was a business\nyesterday.\nAttorney S. Mi\ntie Rock this momiiry to\ngai business.\nConstable J. S. Barnirju\nhas none to Stuttgart\ndatives for sev\nI bn ill\ni h cit v\nHer will\ngO to l.li\nalisaet lo\not' Aitiiei\nnier. was ;t business visitor in Pine\nHi uff yesterday.\nMrs. C. A. Fitzhugh, of McGehee,\nis in the city visiting her son- C. It.\nFitzhugh and family.\n.Meyer Berlin, of Berlin Brothers,\nwent to St. Louis yesterday to pur\nchase cars of horses and mules.\nCharles Weil has returned from a\npleasant visit to his daughter, Mrs.\nLouis Ottenheimer, at Little Rock.\nJ. S. McDonnell, the wealthy mer\nchant-planter of Altheimer, was a\nbusiness visitor in the city yesterday.\nMrs, A. D. Kuhn, of Ogden, Utah,\narrived in the city yesterday and will\nvisit Mr. and Mrs. D. S. Bluthenthal\nand other relatives for several days.\nG. H. Martin, of the Murphy-Martin\nDry Goods Company, has returned\nfrom the Eastern markets, where he\nmade large purchases for his estab\nlishment.\nLOOKING FOR\nBETTER TIMES\nRailway Officers Express Belief That\nPresent Depression Will Be Short\nLived and That Prosperous Business\nWill Be Resumed Soon.\nNearly every railway officer who has\nbeen in attendance at the Interstate\nCommerce Commission meeting with\nreference to the new nine-hour law\nenforcement has expressed the firm\nbelief that the present business de\npression will be short lived, and also\nthat there is no intention cn the part\nof the railways to cut the wages of\nrailway workingmen, says he Little\nRock Democrat. One who is familiar\nwith the testimony given by all the\nrailway men before the commission\nmeeting said concerning the present\nbusiness depression.\n\u201cXot a single official of a single rail\nway line who appeared before the\nj commission expressed the belief that\nthe present industrial depression\nwould be lasting. 'In the testimony of\nnearly every witness before the com\nmission there was a note of confi\ndence- because nearly every one of\ntheta- practically believed that the\nstringency to the money market from\nwhich the country has suffered is not\ndue to fundamental causes. They\npoint out that the crop last year was\ngood; that prices were excellent: that\nt industrial enterprises throughout the\nj country were flourishing. It was\nmerely the inability to command ready\ncash and the hoarding of money by\npanic-stricken individuals which pro\nduced so suddenly the remarkable de\npression from which all hav esufifor\ncd. They practically uniformly ex\npress confidence that the return of\nprosperity will be almost as sudden as\nwas the coming of adversity.\"\nI K\ni n\nti\no\ne\ni a\ni r\nI f<\nr f\nTHE REASON'.\nKatharine^j^ ^jaims that a lie ha*\nfder^-ViuppoM^fou haven'. noticed\nh* talk# through htj nose\nTh\u00ab Iworer-Dere, now \u00abr\u00ab'r\u00bb \u00ab:i\nT worUJrr wo' np\u00bb;'!\u00bb.1 to 4o \"t<\n1\nt\nhms\nWe Are Showing\na complete line of th\nee It I? rated M vYVES\n$^.00 HaTS i\u00abi the\nprevailing colors and\nshapes for the coming\nSpring and Summer.\n4 4<444444<<444444\nSERVICE.\nFour Telephones\nto take your orders\nFour messengers to\ndeliver them.\nALWAYS\nAT YOUR\nSERVICE\nYOU CANNOT DO\nDHTTER.\nORDER FROM\nBEDELL'S PHARMACY\nThe Quality Store\n4 4 4 4 4 4 4 4 4 4 4 4 4 4 4 4 4\nDIXIE LAND\nlaying Cards\u201425 Cents\nREGULAR 50c VALUE.\nThe little pickaninny with her big\nice of watermelon, reproduced in\natural colors on the backs, is just\nio cute for anything. People rave\nver these cards. They have gilt\niges and extra high glazed surface\nud come in a heavy telescope case,\nealers everywhere charge r.n cents\nir this qanlity.\nrvitos o\\ salt; at\nV 